column5: Oh the poor core! It's becoming the rented mule of our body in contemporary yoga practice. Sure, it's important to strengthen the region, just like it's important to strengthen all of the regions of the body, but this area needs some TLC too. This practice will help you let go of deep-seated tension in your core by giving you permission to let go, breathe, and relax. Tune in, it will feel good. Props Needed: One or two blankets.

column3: Quick Relief for Your Shoulders, Lower Back and Hips with Jason Crandell
column5: A targeted practice that brings you relief where you need it most: your shoulders, lower back and hips. Using a strap to open up your shoulders, practice reclined, seated and standing postures to help shed tension and leave you feeling more comfortable. End with a forward fold in sukhasana, with an optional savasana, if you have more time. A great practice to include in your routine for creating better body awareness. Props Needed: A strap.
Ran into some friends in the woods. Scared the crap out of me. All stood up at the same time.

column3: Core for Beginners with Jason Crandell
column5: A quick, complete core practice designed for new students and teachers that work with new students. It contains accessible postures that will strengthen your abdominals, inner-legs and thighs. These postures help trim your midsection and lay the foundation for more challenging work in the future. The practice is also suitable for more experienced students that want a slightly lighter core practice. Props Needed: A block.

column3: Aging & Longevity: Midline Hatha with Annie Carpenter
column5: Engage the full range of your core stabilizers, moving through poses with modifications for more ease or challenge. This simple but strong practice includes Leg Lifts, Side Plank prep, Bird Dog variations, Locust Pose, and Gomukhasana. This class previously aired on September 15, 2022.
